<div class="container">
    <h1>Python Write Excel File</h1>
    <div class="last-updated">📅 Last Updated : 16 Feb 2026</div>

    <div class="intro-text">
        Python provides several modules to write data to Excel files. The most common are <code>xlsxwriter</code>, <code>openpyxl</code>, <code>xlwt</code> (for older <code>.xls</code> format), and <code>pyexcel</code>. Each has its strengths – <code>xlsxwriter</code> excels at formatting, <code>openpyxl</code> supports reading/writing <code>.xlsx</code>, and <code>pyexcel</code> offers a simple array‑based interface.
    </div>

    <h2>1️⃣ Using <code>xlsxwriter</code> Module</h2>
    <p><code>xlsxwriter</code> is a Python module for writing files in the Excel 2007+ XLSX format. It supports writing text, numbers, formulas, and charts, with extensive formatting options.</p>
    <p>Installation:</p>
    <pre><code>pip install xlsxwriter</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Note:</strong> Rows and columns are zero‑indexed. A1 is <code>(0,0)</code>, B1 is <code>(0,1)</code>, etc.</p>
    <pre><code>import xlsxwriter

file_path = r"C:\Users\mk\Desktop\dreamztouchtech.xlsx"
workbook = xlsxwriter.Workbook(file_path)
worksheet = workbook.add_worksheet()

# Using A1 notation
worksheet.write('A1', 'Hello..')
worksheet.write('B1', 'T')
worksheet.write('C1', 'Point')
worksheet.write('D1', 'Tech')
worksheet.write('E1', 'Pvt Ltd')

workbook.close()</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">
        ✅ File saved at: C:\Users\mk\Desktop\dreamztouchtech.xlsx
    </div>

    <h2>2️⃣ Using <code>openpyxl</code> Module</h2>
    <p><code>openpyxl</code> is recommended for reading/writing <code>.xlsx</code>, <code>.xlsm</code>, <code>.xltx</code>, and <code>.xltm</code> files. It allows cell access by row/column indices or by coordinate (e.g., <code>'A1'</code>).</p>
    <pre><code>import openpyxl

wb = openpyxl.Workbook()
sheet = wb.active

# Writing using cell coordinates
sheet.cell(row=1, column=1).value = "ABHAY"
sheet.cell(row=1, column=2).value = "SINGH"
sheet['C1'].value = "CONTENT DEVELOPER"

sheet['A2'].value = "VIVEK"
sheet['B2'].value = "SRIVASTAVA"
sheet['C2'].value = "CONTENT REVIEWER"

wb.save(r"C:\Users\mk\Desktop\dreamztouchtech.xlsx")</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">
        ✅ File saved at: C:\Users\mk\Desktop\dreamztouchtech.xlsx
    </div>

    <h2>3️⃣ Using <code>xlwt</code> Module (Legacy .xls Format)</h2>
    <p><code>xlwt</code> is used for writing older Excel <code>.xls</code> files. It supports formatting, images, charts, and conditional formatting. Note that the <code>.xls</code> format is legacy; prefer XLSX for modern applications.</p>
    <pre><code>import xlwt

wb = xlwt.Workbook()
sheet = wb.add_sheet('Sheet1')

sheet.write(0, 0, "ABHAY")               # A1
sheet.write(0, 1, "SINGH")              # B1
sheet.write(0, 2, "CONTENT DEVELOPER")  # C1

sheet.write(1, 0, "VIVEK")              # A2
sheet.write(1, 1, "SRIVASTAVA")         # B2
sheet.write(1, 2, "CONTENT REVIEWER")   # C2

wb.save(r"C:\Users\mk\Desktop\xlwtfile.xls")</code></pre>
    <div class="note">⚠️ <code>xlwt</code> only supports the older <code>.xls</code> format, which is limited to 65,536 rows and is not supported by newer Excel versions. Use <code>xlsxwriter</code> or <code>openpyxl</code> for XLSX.</div>

    <h2>4️⃣ Using <code>pyexcel</code> Module</h2>
    <p><code>pyexcel</code> provides a simple API to read/write Excel files using arrays. It can handle multiple formats.</p>
    <pre><code>import pyexcel

data = [
    ['ABHAY', 'SINGH', 'CONTENT DEVELOPER', '100% attendance'],
    ['VIVEK', 'SRIVASTAVA', 'CONTENT REVIEWER', '95% attendance']
]

pyexcel.save_as(array=data, dest_file_name=r"C:\Users\mk\Desktop\dreamztouchtech.xlsx")

print("File saved successfully.")</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">
        File saved successfully.
    </div>

    <h2>📊 Comparison of Modules</h2>

  <table class="op-table">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Module</th>
                <th>File Format</th>
                <th>Key Features</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><code>xlsxwriter</code> </th>
                <td><code>.xlsx</code></th>
                <td>Formulas, charts, formatting, images, conditional formatting.</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>openpyxl</code> </th>
                <td><code>.xlsx</code>, <code>.xlsm</code>, <code>.xltx</code>, <code>.xltm</code></th>
                <td>Read/write, supports cell styles, charts, images.</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>xlwt</code> </th>
                <td><code>.xls</code> (legacy)</th>
                <td>Formatting, images, charts (deprecated, limited to 65k rows).</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>pyexcel</code> </th>
                <td>Multiple formats (XLSX, XLS, CSV, etc.)</th>
                <td>Simple array‑based API, easy for quick exports.</th>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="note">
        💡 <strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> For modern Excel files (<code>.xlsx</code>), use <code>xlsxwriter</code> (write‑only, rich formatting) or <code>openpyxl</code> (read/write). For quick array exports, <code>pyexcel</code> is convenient. Avoid <code>xlwt</code> unless you need legacy <code>.xls</code> support.
    </div>

    <div class="intro-text" style="background:#f1f5f9; border-left-color:#64748b;">
        ✅ <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Python offers multiple ways to write Excel files. Choose the module that best fits your needs: <code>xlsxwriter</code> for feature‑rich XLSX creation, <code>openpyxl</code> for reading/writing existing XLSX files, <code>pyexcel</code> for simplicity, and <code>xlwt</code> only for legacy <code>.xls</code> output. Mastering these tools will allow you to generate professional Excel reports from your Python applications.
    </div>

    <footer>
        Python Write Excel File – Complete Guide | xlsxwriter, openpyxl, xlwt, pyexcel
    </footer>
</div>
