<body>
<div class="container">
    <h1>Python Join Arrays</h1>
    <div class="last-updated">📅 Last Updated : 16 Feb 2026</div>

    <div class="intro-text">
        Joining (merging) two arrays means combining their elements into a single array. Python provides several ways to merge arrays, such as using a loop with <code>append()</code>, the <code>+</code> operator (after converting to lists), and the <code>extend()</code> method. Always ensure both arrays have the same data type to avoid errors.
    </div>

    <h2>📦 Creating Two Arrays</h2>
    <pre><code>import array as arr

a = arr.array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9])
b = arr.array('i', [2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])

print("Array A:", a)
print("Array B:", b)</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">
        Array A: array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9])<br>
        Array B: array('i', [2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])
    </div>

    <h2>1️⃣ Join Arrays Using <code>append()</code> (Loop)</h2>
    <p>Iterate over the second array and append each element to the first array.</p>
    <pre><code>import array as arr

a = arr.array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9])
b = arr.array('i', [2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])

for element in b:
    a.append(element)

print("Merged array:", a)</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">Merged array: array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9, 2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])</div>

    <h2>2️⃣ Join Arrays Using <code>+</code> Operator (via List Conversion)</h2>
    <p>Convert arrays to lists, concatenate with <code>+</code>, then convert back to an array.</p>
    <pre><code>import array as arr

a = arr.array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9])
b = arr.array('i', [2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])

list_a = a.tolist()
list_b = b.tolist()
merged_list = list_a + list_b
merged_array = arr.array('i', merged_list)

print("Merged array (using +):", merged_array)</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">Merged array (using +): array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9, 2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])</div>

    <h2>3️⃣ Join Arrays Using <code>extend()</code> Method (via List Conversion)</h2>
    <p>Convert the array to a list, use <code>extend()</code> to add the other list, then convert back.</p>
    <pre><code>import array as arr

a = arr.array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9])
b = arr.array('i', [2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])

list_a = a.tolist()
list_b = b.tolist()
list_a.extend(list_b)
merged_array = arr.array('i', list_a)

print("Merged array (using extend):", merged_array)</code></pre>
    <div class="example-output">Merged array (using extend): array('i', [10, 5, 15, 4, 6, 20, 9, 2, 7, 8, 11, 3, 10])</div>

    <h2>📊 Comparison of Join Methods</h2>
    <table class="op-table">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Method</th>
                <th>Modifies original?</th>
                <th>Requires conversion?</th>
                <th>Ease of use</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong><code>append()</code> in loop</strong> </th>
                <td>Yes (modifies first array)</th>
                <td>No</th>
                <td>Moderate</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong><code>+</code> operator</strong> </th>
                <td>No (creates new array)</th>
                <td>Yes (list conversion)</th>
                <td>High</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong><code>extend()</code></strong> </th>
                <td>No (creates new array via list)</th>
                <td>Yes (list conversion)</th>
                <td>High</th>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="note">
        💡 <strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> To join two arrays, the simplest method is to convert them to lists, merge using <code>+</code> or <code>extend()</code>, and convert back. The loop‑based <code>append()</code> works but modifies the original array. Always ensure both arrays have the same typecode; otherwise, a <code>TypeError</code> will occur.
    </div>

    <div class="intro-text" style="background:#f1f5f9; border-left-color:#64748b;">
        ✅ <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Python’s <code>array</code> module does not directly support concatenation, but you can easily merge arrays using list conversion or manual appending. Understanding these techniques allows you to combine array data efficiently for further processing.
    </div>

    <footer>
        Python Join Arrays – Complete Guide | append, + operator, extend
    </footer>
</div>
</body>
</html>
                
